Valuable Customer NOT Frequent Buyer¶

by (Yasser Ahmed Soliman)¶

Investigation Overview¶

Valuable customers are the profitable ones and not the frequent buyers. From this prespective, I will investigate the database of superstore customers to correlate customer profit vs. other customer characterestics: Sales value, number of Orders, Customer Segment, Shipping mode.

Dataset Overview¶

I have 51,290 customers' records with 24 features. The features type are (string, integer, float). The csv file uses (Unicode) which is different character encodings than ASCII.

Dataset Wrangling¶

In [9]:
# Order_Date conversion from string to datetime
orderdate_str = '%d/%m/%Y'
OrderDate_Errors = []

for i in df['Order_Date']:
    try:
        pd.to_datetime(i, format = orderdate_str)
    except ValueError as error1:
        OrderDate_Errors.append(error1)


if len(OrderDate_Errors) == 0:
    print('Order_Date: Done, all converted')
else:
    print('Order_Date: It is obvious that not all formats match format {}'.format(orderdate_str))       
              
# prepare the error list
OrderDate_Errors_list = pd.DataFrame(OrderDate_Errors)


#======================================================

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

We have 51,290 customers' records with 24 features (as stated above in "df.columns"). Features types are (string, integer, float). The csv file uses (Unicode) which is different character encodings than ASCII.

The dataset has gone through wrangling process: Renaming column lables, checking missing data (isnull), checking for duplication (duplicated), converting date string into datetime, split year, month (with drop, insert), create new column for datat sanity check and for other purposes (Ship_Date - Order_Date)

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am trying to figure out the correlation between profitable customer (valuable customer) with number of ordered items, sales value, customer segmentation, customer shipping mode. Moreover, I would like to apply hypothesis test on one of the feature that I explored using A/B test.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I believe that customer "Customer_ID", customer segmentation "Segment", shipping mode "Ship_Mode", customer sales "Sales", and number of orders for each customer have strong correlation with customer profitability "Profit". In addition, I guess that customer frequency of orders can lead to an insightfull information towards other features.

The frequently used shipping mode is the "Standard Class" which is around 59.6% from total orders. The standard class has a mean waiting time ~ 5 days (WaitTie = Ship_Date - Order_Date) with maximum time 7 days. All other shipping modes have lower time (mean & max). No doubt that other shippimg modes with shorter waiting time comes with higher price. Probably that is the reason that majority of orders are associated with "Standard Class", meaning less cost for the customer and just very few days more before shipping (e.g. First class has mean waiting time = 2days, while standard = 5days).

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

I develped new column called "WaitTime_Day" which is the difference between (Ship_Date - Order_Date) for data integrity where a waiting time with negative value will lead to a deletion of this row.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

I did the following operations:

  1. I replaced spaces with underscore between words in the column lable, and added currency type (USD) for the required ones.
  2. I had a histogram with long tail distribution for both Sales & Profit, therefore for focus and deep look I have limited x-axis view using xlimts.
  3. Pareto 80/20 rule for customer's transactions is not valid, therefore I listed only the top 2% to illustrate the decrease number of transactions among them
  4. I changed date type from string to datetime, and created new columns for Year for next stages analysis
  5. The new created WaitTime_Days column will help to undertand the waiting time for each segment

Statistical proof for Profit correlation with Segment¶

A/B Test: Customer Segmentation¶

  1. Developing two separate tables with equal samples one for Consumer & the other for Corporate Segment
  2. Draw the Null-Hypothesis distribution for Consumer Segment using Mean_Consumer_mean & Std_Corporate, using 10k repeated test for mean & std calculation
  3. Locating the the Mean_Corporate on the Null-Hypothesis dist.

Hypothesis¶

  1. H0, Null Hypothesis: Corporate Segment customers is same as the Consumer Segment or worse in profit
  2. H1, Alternative Hypothesis: Corporate Segment customers is profitable than Consumer Segment.
  3. This is Right-Tailed test
$$H_0: \mu_{Corporate} - \mu_{Consumer} \leq 0$$

$$H_1: \mu_{Corporate} - \mu_{Consumer} > 0$$

A/B Test: Alternative Solution Method 2 (using Confidence Interval)¶

  1. H0, Null Hypothesis: Corporate Segment customers is same as the Consumer Segmente in profit.
  2. H1, Alternative Hypothesis: Corporate Segment customers is not same as Consumer Segment profit.
  3. This is two-tailed test
$$H_0: \mu_{Corporate} = \mu_{Consumer} $$

$$H_1: \mu_{Corporate} \neq \mu_{Consumer} $$
